node.text:
Did you know that in 1936, Aeronautics was an Olympic event? 🥇✈️
Switzerland’s Hermann Schreiber was awarded an Olympic gold medal for merit in Aeronautics for a glider flight that took place over the Alps in 1935! And there were plenty of actual aeronautical feats to witness at the Berlin games. The Hindenburg hovered in the skies over the Olympic stadium, painted with the Olympic rings. The first public demonstration of the Messerschmitt Bf 109 prototype took place. And the Museum's Bücker Bü-133C Jungmeister was there too! 
Captain Alexander Papana of the Rumanian Air Force had placed fourth in the two-man bobsled event in the 1932 Lake Placid Olympics and had won the gold medal in the 1933 World Championships. Papana participated in the Olympics aeronautics demonstrations in 1936 and his Bücker Bü-133C Jungmeister, pictured here, featured Olympic rings on its tail. #Olympics

node.text:
Splashdown! 50 years ago today, Apollo 15 returned to Earth as command module Endeavour splashed down in the Pacific Ocean. One of the three Apollo 15 parachutes failed to inflate fully, so descent velocity was 2.8 mph faster than planned. The capsule was designed to land safely with just two parachutes, so the crew was OK.
After splashdown, the astronauts were assisted out of the command module by Navy divers and were flown to the recovery ship USS Okinawa by helicopter. The Apollo 15 astronauts were the first lunar surface explorers to not be quarantined after their mission. #Apollo50

node.text:
On this day in 1945, the Boeing B-29 Superfortress "Enola Gay" dropped atomic bomb “Little Boy” on Hiroshima, Japan. It was the first time an atomic weapon was used in combat.

The Boeing B-29 Superfortress was the most advanced propeller-driven airplane in the world in 1945, making it the ultimate definition of a “modern” airplane. Designed to fly farther, faster, and higher than any other bomber, the combination of the B-29’s aerodynamic, structural and propulsion innovations allowed it to carry 5,000 pounds of bombs to a target 1,500 miles away while cruising at 220 miles per hour at altitudes up to 30,000 feet. It also had advanced tricycle landing gear and was the first bomber to have an analog computer-controlled defensive armament system and a pressurized and heated fuselage that meant the 11-person crew did not have to wear oxygen masks and heavy, bulky clothing during long missions.

"Enola Gay" is currently on display at the Steven F. Udvar-Hazy Center in Chantilly, Virginia.

node.text:
Today in 1943, the Women Airforce Service Pilots (WASP) was officially formed.

With the merging of the Women Auxiliary Ferrying Squadron (WAFS) and the Women’s Flying Training Detachment (WFTD), the WASP flew 60 million miles during World War II, piloting military aircraft on domestic missions. These women flew the entire range of aircraft manufactured for the war.
#BecauseOfHerStory

Rescuing people at sea has always been a hazardous undertaking — but for 231 years, the U.S. Coast Guard has risen to the challenge.
The Sikorsky HH-52A, the first @USCG aircraft to join our collection, helps us tell that story. The HH-52 was the Coast Guard’s first turbine-powered helicopter and the first that could land in the water next to vessels or personnel in distress without using awkward floats, making it the most effective air-sea rescue helicopter of its time. The Coast Guard operated 99 HH-52s between 1962 and 1989, saving 15,000 lives.
The Coast Guard was founded on this day in 1790.

node.text:
Selfie or it didn’t happen.

On this day in 2005, Space Shuttle Discovery astronaut Stephen K. Robinson became the first person to do a spacewalk underneath a space shuttle orbiter. 

Mission managers sent Robinson under Discovery's belly because they had concerns that a pair of protruding gap fillers, bookmark-like strips of cloth infused with ceramic, could disrupt the aerodynamics of the orbiter during reentry and affect the shuttle’s temperature. As seen on image 1️⃣, he managed to capture a selfie during the mission. In image 2️⃣ Robinson is attached to a foot restraint on the International Space Station’s Canadarm2.

node.text:
Another Wright first. Today in 1909, the US Army Signal Corps accepted the 1909 Wright Military Flyer, the first airplane purchased and put into service by any government.

The bid from the US Army Signal Corps required that it:
- Be easily assembled and disassembled so that an army wagon could transport it
- Be able to carry two people,
- Be able to reach a speed of at least 40 mph in still air
- Be able to remain in the air for at least one hour without landing
- Be able to land safely without needing a prepared spot and without causing any damage that would prevent it from immediately starting another flight

The purchase price was set at $25,000 with ten percent added for each full mile per hour of speed over the required 40 mph and ten percent deducted for each full mile per hour under 40 mph. The Wright Military Flyer clocked in at 42 mph, making the final sale price of the airplane $30,000.

Flying into the history books 👩‍✈️ 110 years ago today, Harriet Quimby became the first American woman to earn a pilot's license. Quimby was one of the most popular pioneering female aviators and she became an instant sensation in 1912 after becoming the first woman to fly solo across the English Channel.
#IdeasThatDefy #BecauseOfHerStory #WomensHistory #WomeninAviation #AmericanHistory #AmericanWomensHistory

Driving on the Moon 🚘 🌑
50 years ago today, astronauts used the Lunar Roving Vehicle (LRV) on the Moon for the first time as part of the Apollo 15 mission. The LRV was stowed on the descent stage of the Lunar Module and deployed upon arrival at the lunar surface.
It was powered by battery and was operated with a spacecraft "stick," rather than a steering wheel, and could move forward and backwards. The Apollo 15 astronauts traveled over 25 kilometers on the lunar surface, but thanks to the LRV, they didn't have to do it on foot.
The LRV travelled at an average speed of 9.6 km/hr, reaching speeds of 12 km/hr over level lunar terrain. LRVs were also taken on the Apollo 16 and 17 missions. All LRVs were left on the Moon, but this "Qualification Test Unit," which is in our collection, was a very close replica of the units that flew.
Learn more about how the LRV changed the game at the link in our bio. #AirSpacePhoto #Apollo50

node.text:
This photo stops us in our (rover) tracks every time.
50 years ago right now, Apollo 15 lunar module "Falcon" landed on the Moon. Astronauts David Scott and Jim Irwin spent 66 hours, 54 minutes, 53 seconds on the lunar surface. The astronauts landed "Falcon" in the Hadley Rille region of the Moon, at the foot of the Apennine mountain range. The location was chosen for its proximity to Mare Imbrium and the mountains, and the opportunity for geologic study.
Learn more about Apollo 15 at the link in our bio. #Apollo50

node.text:
“One giant sip for mankind.”

Today in 1985, STS-51-F launched carrying carbonated beverages into space for the first time. The companies had to develop a can that would work in weightlessness to keep the cola fizzy without spewing out of the can. It appears that neither won the taste test however, as the astronauts said the cola was too foamy to be tasty. 

“One giant sip for mankind” was Pepsi’s slogan for the campaign.
#Smithsonian80s
